1. What did loss.backward() actually do?
Imagine your model has millions of knobs (weights). After a wrong prediction, you need to know which knobs caused the mistake and by how much.
loss.backward() does exactly that using the chain rule of calculus. It walks backwards through every operation in your model — from the loss all the way back to 
the first layer — and computes a gradient for every single weight. A gradient is just a number that says: "if you increase this weight, the loss goes up/down by this much."
Forward pass:  input → layer1 → layer2 → output → loss
                                                      ↓
Backward pass: loss → ∂loss/∂layer2 → ∂loss/∂layer1 → ∂loss/∂weights
Then optimizer.step() uses those gradients to nudge every weight slightly in the direction that reduces loss. loss.backward() computes the blame. optimizer.step() acts on it.
The intuition: you got a test wrong. loss.backward() figures out which study habits caused the mistake. optimizer.step() fixes those habits slightly.

2. What is attention_mask preventing?
When you batch sentences together, shorter ones get padded with zeros to match the longest sentence:
"I love ML"     → [101, 1045, 2293, 19081, 102,  0,    0,    0   ]
"Transformers"  → [101, 19081, 102,  0,    0,    0,    0,    0   ]
                                          ↑ these are fake padding tokens
Without attention_mask, the model would try to learn from those zeros — treating padding as real words. This corrupts the learning signal completely.
attention_mask is a parallel array of 1s and 0s:
[1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0]  ← 1 = real token, 0 = ignore this
The model's attention mechanism uses this mask to refuse to look at padding positions during both training and inference. It's like putting a sticky note over 
irrelevant parts of a page before reading. Why it matters for you specifically: Your GCG adversarial attack worked by carefully choosing which token positions to perturb. 
The attention mask is part of what determined which positions had real influence on the output — your attack was essentially exploiting the unmasked positions.

